const searchBtn = document.getElementById('searchBtn');
const locationInput = document.getElementById('location');
const weatherContainer = document.getElementById('weatherContainer');

const apiUrl = 'https://api.weatherapi.com/v1/current.json?key=<YOUR_API_KEY>&q=';

const showWeather = (data) => {
  const { temp_c, temp_f, condition, humidity, wind_kph, wind_dir } = data.current;
  const location = data.location.name;

  const html = `
    <h2>${location}</h2>
    <p>${condition.text}</p>
    <p>Temperature: ${temp_c}°C / ${temp_f}°F</p>
    <p>Humidity: ${humidity}%</p>
    <p>Wind: ${wind_kph} km/h ${wind_dir}</p>
  `;

  weatherContainer.innerHTML = html;
};

const fetchWeather = () => {
  const location = locationInput.value;
  if (location.trim() === '') {
    alert('Please enter a location.');
  } else {
    fetch(apiUrl + location)
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => showWeather(data))
      .catch(error => console.log(error));
  }
};

searchBtn.addEventListener('click', fetchWeather);
```

In this example, we create an input field for the user to enter a location and a search button to initiate the weather search. The `apiUrl` constant contains the URL of the weather API endpoint, with a `q` parameter for the user's search query.

When the user clicks the search button, we retrieve the location from the input field and validate it for empty values. If the location is valid, we make a request to the weather API endpoint using the Fetch API. 

When we receive the data, we extract the relevant information, such as temperature, weather condition, and wind speed and direction, and display it in the DOM. We use template literals to create an HTML string containing the required information, and set this string as the innerHTML of the `weatherContainer` element.

